  content obj_root_law_sections_16_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_16_footnotes
  sourcePage 16
obj_root_law_sections_16_content:
  string
  line 16
  line `20. Repeal and saving s. — ( 1 ) The Imports and Exports (Control) Act, 1947 (18 of 1947) and the`
  line `Foreign Trade (Development and Regulation) Ordinance, 1992 (Ord. 11 of 1992) are hereby repealed.`
  line `( 2 ) The repeal of the Imports and Exports (Control) Act, 1947 (18 of 1947) shall, however, not`
  line `affect, —`
  line `( a ) the previous operation of the Act so repealed or anything duly done or suffered thereunder; or`
  line `( b ) any right, privilege, obligation or liability acquired, accrued or incurred under the Act so`
  line `repealed; or`
  line `( c ) any penalty, confiscation or punishment incurred in respect of any contravention under the`
  line `Act so repealed; or`
  line `( d ) any proceeding or remedy in respe ct of any such right, privilege, obligation, liability, penalty,`
  line `confiscat ion or punishment as aforesaid,`
  line `and any such proceeding or remedy may be instituted, continued or enforced, and any such penalty,`
  line `confiscation or punishment may be imposed or made as if that Act had not been repealed.`
  line `( 3 ) Notwithstanding the repeal of the Foreign Trade (Development and Regulation) Ordinance, 1992`
  line `(Ord. 11 of 1992), anything done or any action taken under the said Ordinance shall be deemed to have`
  line `been done or taken under the corresponding provisions of this Act.`
obj_root_law_sections_16_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_17:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-17
  sectionNo (17)
  orderNo 17
  title `Page 17`
  content obj_root_law_sections_17_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_17_footnotes
  sourcePage 17
obj_root_law_sections_17_content:
  string
  line 17
  line `STATEMENT OF OBJECTS AND REASONS`
  line `It is now generally acknowledged that foreign trade is a driving force of economic activity.`
  line `Technology, investment and production are b ecoming increasingly interdependent upon each other and`
  line `foreign trade brings these elements together and spurs economic growth.`
  line `2. The Imports and Exports (Control) Act, 1947 was made in different circumstances. Although it has`
  line `been amended from time to time, the Act does not provide an adequate legal framework for the`
  line `development and promotion of India ’ s foreign trade. Bes i des, in July, 1991 and August, 1991, major`
  line `changes in trade policy were made by the Government of India. The goals of the new trade policy are to`
  line `increase p roductivity and competitiveness and to achieve a strong export perfo r mance. T he Export and`
  line `Import Policy is a vital part of trade policy. The basic law governing foreign trade must serve as an`
  line `instrument to create an environment that will provide a strong impetus to exports, facilitate imports and`
  line `render export activity more profitable.`
  line `3. It is, therefore, considered necessary to enact a new law repealing the existing law. The Bill intends`
  line `to achieve these objectives.`
  line `N EW D ELHI; P. CHIDAMBARAM.`
  line `The 26 th March, 1992.`
obj_root_law_sections_17_footnotes:
  string
  line
